Title: Eighth Grade | Official Trailer HD | A24
Comment:
I am 24 years old now, and I remember being in 8th grade 10 years ago, as if it was yesterday. What made it even ‚Äúworse‚Äù is my dad was an 8th grade teacher at the same school I went to while I was in 8th grade. My dad was embarrassing and awkward, ‚Äúcool‚Äù teacher (still is tbh haha! But it‚Äôs fun now), everyone in the school knew who he was, and therefore everyone knew who I was. So I ALWAYS stood out, even if I didn‚Äôt want to.

I can‚Äôt sit through this movie without getting up and walking out of the room, because it brings back so many memories and makes me cringe. But that just shows it‚Äôs effectiveness! This movie is amazing and probably one of the only movies that accurately portrays what it‚Äôs like to be in middle school. Trying to impress the popular crowd, talking to boys, dealing with parents, and just all the other awkward moments that come with becoming a teenager; I remember going through every single moment of it all. It makes me laugh, cringe, breaks my heart, and just brings back a lot of embarrassing moments from that time of my life that, even looking back on them now, I still wouldn‚Äôt change today. Going through what you go through as a teenager shapes you into who you‚Äôre going to become in the future, whether you believe that or not.

I used to say that I would ‚Äúslap my younger self‚Äù, but now I think if I could go back in time, I would give her/myself a hug and tell her that ‚ÄúDad is right, just like he always is. Everything is going to turn out okay. You‚Äôll find your best friends for life, fall in love a few times, meet the love of your life, finally start to believe and have confidence in yourself, discover your passions, and realize everything really is going to be all right.‚Äù

So thank you, Bo. Thank you for making me relive my childhood for a second time üòÇ

Title: Eighth Grade | Official Trailer HD | A24
Comment:
As a 9th grader, I am SO GLAD that an adult-who GETS what it's like to finish middle school in this age-made an amazing movie like this.
The emphasis on the acne the whole movie, like you're seeing it through her eyes because that's actually how the main character feels about her face. No "beauty filter" outside of her phone, just insecurity
The fact that so many teachers try to get hip with the kids and bring up memes that have been dead for a good few years
The behind-the-scenes struggle with emotional pain the girl has to go through, hugging her dad who's always there even if he sorta embarasses her. As someone who's emotionally unstable, I've had times where I just have to hug my mom and cry my heart out
Social anxiety disorder, the fear of being around lots of other people. One of my closest friends has it

This has gotta be one of my favorite movies of all time...it brought me to tears...

It's really easy to sympathize with Kayla, as almost everyone goes through what she does, more or less! It catapulted me back in time and brought back memories of my own struggles and feelings, when I was that age.

Comment: Take it from a person who literally saw himself in that girl...  Nothing ever changes, those "dorky adults" and most importantly that  dad went through EVERYTHING you went through. My pool party nightmare involved me actually shaving my armpits because I felt ashamed of my body.  All the other boys were narrow shouldered and hairless and I did not like being different. The reality was I was a full grown man at 14 with muscles and perfect bone structure.  There was no need for me to be ashamed, and the same goes with all of you.   I am saying this in the hopes that some of you 14 years olds in this comments section will listen to me...  If you are going through an awkward time, let one of your parents know. Title: Eighth Grade | Official Trailer HD | A24
Comment:
I definitely wanna see this. Middle school was the absolute worst part of my grade school life. I was bullied worse during those two years than grades 1-6 combined. It was a nightmare and I hated it so much. I was so happy when I graduated, even though a good chunk of the kids would be moving on to the same high school. HS was still easier for me, at least in terms of bullying. People were still assholes and a number of them hated me for no reason, but HS brought me my very first legitimate group of real friends. Yes, I had a couple of friends growing up, but I was always the very shy, awkward one that liked to be invisible more than seen. Obviously, I was prime bully fodder. 

Watching this movie will probably be very relatable to me on some aspects, but, as a child who grew up in the 80s and 90s, who was bullied by her peers and mother, I doubt it could capture the experiences that led to my PTSD later in life. Her father, especially, looks very supportive and loving, which I guess I can relate to, as my father was a very loving man. I'll always miss him.

Comment:
Dear Bo Burnham,
The probability that you will read this is very low, but there is a part of me that needs to write this to let you know the beautiful, spectacular piece of art named Eighth Grade is one of the greatest movies I have ever seen. You perfectly captured the struggle of not just a 13-year-old girl, but of a human being. This is an accurate portrayal of life's struggles and the emotions that everyone deals with at some point in his or her life. Most importantly you showed the possibility of getting through the tough times and accepting ourselves for the weird, quirky individuals we are. I can tell the genuine feelings that you poured into this movie, and for that I say thank you! I feel this will have a great influence among pre-teens and teenagers (I am one of them), along with future generations. 

Sincerely,
An awkward human being

P.S. Tell Elsie Fisher thank you for an amazing performance!

Comment: I'm sorry but I just can't be interested in these "everyday Joe" movies (this, and the one about the gay high schooler). Movies should be portals into different worlds, galaxies, dimensions, etc., and when they are realistic they should depict extraordinary events happening to interesting and intriguing people who have to overcome immense hardships. The fact that movies like this are basically just strapping a go pro to an everyday students head just seems so boring and uneventful, and I've already been through 8th grade, so what's the point? And the main source of drama is just the everyday struggle of some kid who's well off in a first world country, aimlessly going through the motions of life. How can anyone find this interesting?

Comment: I‚Äôm a freshman now. Back in eight grade things were simple. Everyone knew everyone. No one was sexual. Only like one kid drank or did drugs. Social wise, it was the same just different people and less drama. Now I‚Äôm a freshman, 5ft tall, antipubescent and it kinda sucks. I made new friends after like 3 months and they‚Äôre pretty lit for the most part. However, I‚Äôm lucky. A lot of these people I thought I used to know are living in the moment, either following or leading the wrong crowd; doing drugs, drinking, having sex, spreading rumors... everything kinda just changed. I‚Äôm driving now. I honestly think that focusing on my grades and on good quality people has saved me thus far. Everyone else is either not focused on grades and is having sex and doing drugs. I still hang out with friends and stuff, but literally know one who is ranked #1 like me is doing drugs or having sex. Like only one maybe drank once at a party she was trapped in or something. Point being: everything and everyone changed but my grades saved me. Stick to them.

I‚Äôm in 8th grade right now, dunno why everybody is saying how bad 8th grade is/was. I guess the reason why is the fact that I never got into the social media side of being at my age (14). I do think me not going into the social media circle has befitted me greatly so I haven‚Äôt had to constantly think that I have to be better looking etc. I‚Äôm not the ‚Äòpopular‚Äô one at school but I don‚Äôt care, I care about being happy for who I am instead of having people to tell me how cool I am constantly. To recap: social media is just plain not good for people at my age because of what it does to everyday people and gives us false expectations of what we should be.

Edit: 
To clarify: I didn‚Äôt mean my comment to get this much attention, it was just my two cents. What I meant by ‚Äòunrealistic expectations‚Äô is that on social media almost everybody is trying to show off the best of themselves and showing their best photos of them. Out of no where 11th grade I was 200lbs shredded started dating a hot girl and suddenly I was "popular" and had all these new "friends." Just a little inspiration for anyone going through something like that everything has a purpose, it gets better and you're the only one who can change it.

1. A beautiful, well-done and understanding coming-of age film that highlights the ups and downs of growing up with a bit of quirkiness to keep your interest.
2. A pretentious, pandering film that tween and teenage girls will enjoy the most, in addition to those who believe that Burnham can do no wrong.

Comment: I'm so glad I didn't go through high school when everyone had a feckin' phone in their hands. Believe it or not, life was pretty decent. I know some people think it's wonderful that their children have a way to communicate with them, such as in an emergency, but how many children's lives have been ruined by them? How many young lives have been destroyed because they cannot pay attention to something for 10 seconds that isn't in their palm? How many young girls have killed themselves because of online harassment? How many articles of child pornography have been produced, because some moronic parent gave a horny teenager a device with a camera and access to the internet? Everything comes at a cost, and we are already seeing the costs of technology.

Title: Eighth Grade | Official Trailer HD | A24
Comment: A24 stays coming through!! This looks like everything Edge of Seventeen wanted to be but failed at being. This actually looks realistic, has a realistic looking cast (the main girl isn't stick thin! my chubby middle school self would have cried to see this), and doesn't automatically make fun of the current youngest generation for being into social media! I haven't been in 8th grade for almost a decade now, but it was truly the worst time of my life and this is showcasing that perfectly. This seems like an accurate representation of preteen/teenage life in 2018 (down to the kpop obsession üòÇ) and even though I'm 21, I'm thrilled. Finally, an awkward female lead that isn't just "quirky cute awkward"...she actually IS. I'm rambling but I love tf out of this.
